{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_017hU1E71Cxb7no5yQUx7Bxd","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→use crate::shared::error::{AppError, AppResult};\n     2→\n     3→use super::model::{JournalEvent, JournalEventType};\n     4→\n     5→/// Validates that a new event's sequence follows the last known sequence.\n     6→/// The first event must have sequence 1.\n     7→pub fn validate_sequence(last_sequence: u64, event: &JournalEvent) -> AppResult<()> {\n     8→    let expected = last_sequence + 1;\n     9→    if event.sequence != expected {\n    10→        return Err(AppError::JournalSequence {\n    11→            details: format!(\"expected sequence {expected}, got {}\", event.sequence),\n    12→        });\n    13→    }\n    14→    Ok(())\n    15→}\n    16→\n    17→/// Serializes a journal event to a single NDJSON line (no trailing newline).\n    18→pub fn serialize_event(event: &JournalEvent) -> AppResult<String> {\n    19→    Ok(serde_json::to_string(event)?)\n    20→}\n    21→\n    22→/// Deserializes a single NDJSON line into a journal event.\n    23→pub fn deserialize_event(line: &str) -> AppResult<JournalEvent> {\n    24→    let trimmed = line.trim();\n    25→    if trimmed.is_empty() {\n    26→        return Err(AppError::CorruptRecord {\n    27→            file: \"journal.ndjson\".to_owned(),\n    28→            details: \"empty line in journal\".to_owned(),\n    29→        });\n    30→    }\n    31→    serde_json::from_str(trimmed).map_err(|e| AppError::CorruptRecord {\n    32→        file: \"journal.ndjson\".to_owned(),\n    33→        details: format!(\"invalid journal event: {e}\"),\n    34→    })\n    35→}\n    36→\n    37→/// Parses the full contents of a journal.ndjson file into ordered events.\n    38→/// Validates monotonic sequence ordering and journal integrity (first event\n    39→/// must be `project_created` with sequence 1).\n    40→pub fn parse_journal(contents: &str) -> AppResult<Vec<JournalEvent>> {\n    41→    let mut events = Vec::new();\n    42→    let mut last_sequence = 0u64;\n    43→\n    44→    for line in contents.lines() {\n    45→        if line.trim().is_empty() {\n    46→            continue;\n    47→        }\n    48→        let event = deserialize_event(line)?;\n    49→        validate_sequence(last_sequence, &event)?;\n    50→        last_sequence = event.sequence;\n    51→        events.push(event);\n    52→    }\n    53→\n    54→    validate_journal_integrity(&events)?;\n    55→\n    56→    Ok(events)\n    57→}\n    58→\n    59→/// Validates that a journal has the required structure:\n    60→/// - Must not be empty (must contain at least the initial `project_created` event)\n    61→/// - First event must be `project_created` with sequence 1\n    62→pub fn validate_journal_integrity(events: &[JournalEvent]) -> AppResult<()> {\n    63→    if events.is_empty() {\n    64→        return Err(AppError::CorruptRecord {\n    65→            file: \"journal.ndjson\".to_owned(),\n    66→            details: \"journal is empty — must contain at least the initial project_created event\"\n    67→                .to_owned(),\n    68→        });\n    69→    }\n    70→\n    71→    let first = &events[0];\n    72→    if first.event_type != JournalEventType::ProjectCreated {\n    73→        return Err(AppError::CorruptRecord {\n    74→            file: \"journal.ndjson\".to_owned(),\n    75→            details: format!(\n    76→                \"first journal event type is '{:?}', expected 'project_created'\",\n    77→                first.event_type\n    78→            ),\n    79→        });\n    80→    }\n    81→\n    82→    Ok(())\n    83→}\n    84→\n    85→/// Returns the last sequence number from a set of events, or 0 if empty.\n    86→pub fn last_sequence(events: &[JournalEvent]) -> u64 {\n    87→    events.last().map_or(0, |e| e.sequence)\n    88→}\n    89→\n    90→// ── Lifecycle event builders ────────────────────────────────────────────────\n    91→\n    92→use chrono::{DateTime, Utc};\n    93→use crate::shared::domain::{RunId, StageId};\n    94→\n    95→/// Build a `run_started` journal event.\n    96→pub fn run_started_event(\n    97→    sequence: u64,\n    98→    timestamp: DateTime<Utc>,\n    99→    run_id: &RunId,\n   100→    first_stage: StageId,\n   101→) -> JournalEvent {\n   102→    JournalEvent {\n   103→        sequence,\n   104→        timestamp,\n   105→        event_type: JournalEventType::RunStarted,\n   106→        details: serde_json::json!({\n   107→            \"run_id\": run_id.as_str(),\n   108→            \"first_stage\": first_stage.as_str(),\n   109→        }),\n   110→    }\n   111→}\n   112→\n   113→/// Build a `stage_entered` journal event.\n   114→pub fn stage_entered_event(\n   115→    sequence: u64,\n   116→    timestamp: DateTime<Utc>,\n   117→    run_id: &RunId,\n   118→    stage_id: StageId,\n   119→    cycle: u32,\n   120→    attempt: u32,\n   121→) -> JournalEvent {\n   122→    JournalEvent {\n   123→        sequence,\n   124→        timestamp,\n   125→        event_type: JournalEventType::StageEntered,\n   126→        details: serde_json::json!({\n   127→            \"run_id\": run_id.as_str(),\n   128→            \"stage_id\": stage_id.as_str(),\n   129→            \"cycle\": cycle,\n   130→            \"attempt\": attempt,\n   131→        }),\n   132→    }\n   133→}\n   134→\n   135→/// Build a `stage_completed` journal event.\n   136→#[allow(clippy::too_many_arguments)]\n   137→pub fn stage_completed_event(\n   138→    sequence: u64,\n   139→    timestamp: DateTime<Utc>,\n   140→    run_id: &RunId,\n   141→    stage_id: StageId,\n   142→    cycle: u32,\n   143→    attempt: u32,\n   144→    payload_id: &str,\n   145→    artifact_id: &str,\n   146→) -> JournalEvent {\n   147→    JournalEvent {\n   148→        sequence,\n   149→        timestamp,\n   150→        event_type: JournalEventType::StageCompleted,\n   151→        details: serde_json::json!({\n   152→            \"run_id\": run_id.as_str(),\n   153→            \"stage_id\": stage_id.as_str(),\n   154→            \"cycle\": cycle,\n   155→            \"attempt\": attempt,\n   156→            \"payload_id\": payload_id,\n   157→            \"artifact_id\": artifact_id,\n   158→        }),\n   159→    }\n   160→}\n   161→\n   162→/// Build a `run_completed` journal event.\n   163→pub fn run_completed_event(\n   164→    sequence: u64,\n   165→    timestamp: DateTime<Utc>,\n   166→    run_id: &RunId,\n   167→    completion_rounds: u32,\n   168→) -> JournalEvent {\n   169→    JournalEvent {\n   170→        sequence,\n   171→        timestamp,\n   172→        event_type: JournalEventType::RunCompleted,\n   173→        details: serde_json::json!({\n   174→            \"run_id\": run_id.as_str(),\n   175→            \"completion_rounds\": completion_rounds,\n   176→        }),\n   177→    }\n   178→}\n   179→\n   180→/// Build a `run_failed` journal event.\n   181→pub fn run_failed_event(\n   182→    sequence: u64,\n   183→    timestamp: DateTime<Utc>,\n   184→    run_id: &RunId,\n   185→    stage_id: StageId,\n   186→    failure_class: &str,\n   187→    message: &str,\n   188→) -> JournalEvent {\n   189→    JournalEvent {\n   190→        sequence,\n   191→        timestamp,\n   192→        event_type: JournalEventType::RunFailed,\n   193→        details: serde_json::json!({\n   194→            \"run_id\": run_id.as_str(),\n   195→            \"stage_id\": stage_id.as_str(),\n   196→            \"failure_class\": failure_class,\n   197→            \"message\": message,\n   198→        }),\n   199→    }\n   200→}\n   201→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"04681ab0-f55e-4c96-b8ca-61b2a1e590bf","uuid":"ae8a21b4-c50e-4ae9-a0dc-1e683f4427d1","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/project_run_record/journal.rs","content":"use crate::shared::error::{AppError, AppResult};\n\nuse super::model::{JournalEvent, JournalEventType};\n\n/// Validates that a new event's sequence follows the last known sequence.\n/// The first event must have sequence 1.\npub fn validate_sequence(last_sequence: u64, event: &JournalEvent) -> AppResult<()> {\n    let expected = last_sequence + 1;\n    if event.sequence != expected {\n        return Err(AppError::JournalSequence {\n            details: format!(\"expected sequence {expected}, got {}\", event.sequence),\n        });\n    }\n    Ok(())\n}\n\n/// Serializes a journal event to a single NDJSON line (no trailing newline).\npub fn serialize_event(event: &JournalEvent) -> AppResult<String> {\n    Ok(serde_json::to_string(event)?)\n}\n\n/// Deserializes a single NDJSON line into a journal event.\npub fn deserialize_event(line: &str) -> AppResult<JournalEvent> {\n    let trimmed = line.trim();\n    if trimmed.is_empty() {\n        return Err(AppError::CorruptRecord {\n            file: \"journal.ndjson\".to_owned(),\n            details: \"empty line in journal\".to_owned(),\n        });\n    }\n    serde_json::from_str(trimmed).map_err(|e| AppError::CorruptRecord {\n        file: \"journal.ndjson\".to_owned(),\n        details: format!(\"invalid journal event: {e}\"),\n    })\n}\n\n/// Parses the full contents of a journal.ndjson file into ordered events.\n/// Validates monotonic sequence ordering and journal integrity (first event\n/// must be `project_created` with sequence 1).\npub fn parse_journal(contents: &str) -> AppResult<Vec<JournalEvent>> {\n    let mut events = Vec::new();\n    let mut last_sequence = 0u64;\n\n    for line in contents.lines() {\n        if line.trim().is_empty() {\n            continue;\n        }\n        let event = deserialize_event(line)?;\n        validate_sequence(last_sequence, &event)?;\n        last_sequence = event.sequence;\n        events.push(event);\n    }\n\n    validate_journal_integrity(&events)?;\n\n    Ok(events)\n}\n\n/// Validates that a journal has the required structure:\n/// - Must not be empty (must contain at least the initial `project_created` event)\n/// - First event must be `project_created` with sequence 1\npub fn validate_journal_integrity(events: &[JournalEvent]) -> AppResult<()> {\n    if events.is_empty() {\n        return Err(AppError::CorruptRecord {\n            file: \"journal.ndjson\".to_owned(),\n            details: \"journal is empty — must contain at least the initial project_created event\"\n                .to_owned(),\n        });\n    }\n\n    let first = &events[0];\n    if first.event_type != JournalEventType::ProjectCreated {\n        return Err(AppError::CorruptRecord {\n            file: \"journal.ndjson\".to_owned(),\n            details: format!(\n                \"first journal event type is '{:?}', expected 'project_created'\",\n                first.event_type\n            ),\n        });\n    }\n\n    Ok(())\n}\n\n/// Returns the last sequence number from a set of events, or 0 if empty.\npub fn last_sequence(events: &[JournalEvent]) -> u64 {\n    events.last().map_or(0, |e| e.sequence)\n}\n\n// ── Lifecycle event builders ────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\nuse chrono::{DateTime, Utc};\nuse crate::shared::domain::{RunId, StageId};\n\n/// Build a `run_started` journal event.\npub fn run_started_event(\n    sequence: u64,\n    timestamp: DateTime<Utc>,\n    run_id: &RunId,\n    first_stage: StageId,\n) -> JournalEvent {\n    JournalEvent {\n        sequence,\n        timestamp,\n        event_type: JournalEventType::RunStarted,\n        details: serde_json::json!({\n            \"run_id\": run_id.as_str(),\n            \"first_stage\": first_stage.as_str(),\n        }),\n    }\n}\n\n/// Build a `stage_entered` journal event.\npub fn stage_entered_event(\n    sequence: u64,\n    timestamp: DateTime<Utc>,\n    run_id: &RunId,\n    stage_id: StageId,\n    cycle: u32,\n    attempt: u32,\n) -> JournalEvent {\n    JournalEvent {\n        sequence,\n        timestamp,\n        event_type: JournalEventType::StageEntered,\n        details: serde_json::json!({\n            \"run_id\": run_id.as_str(),\n            \"stage_id\": stage_id.as_str(),\n            \"cycle\": cycle,\n            \"attempt\": attempt,\n        }),\n    }\n}\n\n/// Build a `stage_completed` journal event.\n#[allow(clippy::too_many_arguments)]\npub fn stage_completed_event(\n    sequence: u64,\n    timestamp: DateTime<Utc>,\n    run_id: &RunId,\n    stage_id: StageId,\n    cycle: u32,\n    attempt: u32,\n    payload_id: &str,\n    artifact_id: &str,\n) -> JournalEvent {\n    JournalEvent {\n        sequence,\n        timestamp,\n        event_type: JournalEventType::StageCompleted,\n        details: serde_json::json!({\n            \"run_id\": run_id.as_str(),\n            \"stage_id\": stage_id.as_str(),\n            \"cycle\": cycle,\n            \"attempt\": attempt,\n            \"payload_id\": payload_id,\n            \"artifact_id\": artifact_id,\n        }),\n    }\n}\n\n/// Build a `run_completed` journal event.\npub fn run_completed_event(\n    sequence: u64,\n    timestamp: DateTime<Utc>,\n    run_id: &RunId,\n    completion_rounds: u32,\n) -> JournalEvent {\n    JournalEvent {\n        sequence,\n        timestamp,\n        event_type: JournalEventType::RunCompleted,\n        details: serde_json::json!({\n            \"run_id\": run_id.as_str(),\n            \"completion_rounds\": completion_rounds,\n        }),\n    }\n}\n\n/// Build a `run_failed` journal event.\npub fn run_failed_event(\n    sequence: u64,\n    timestamp: DateTime<Utc>,\n    run_id: &RunId,\n    stage_id: StageId,\n    failure_class: &str,\n    message: &str,\n) -> JournalEvent {\n    JournalEvent {\n        sequence,\n        timestamp,\n        event_type: JournalEventType::RunFailed,\n        details: serde_json::json!({\n            \"run_id\": run_id.as_str(),\n            \"stage_id\": stage_id.as_str(),\n            \"failure_class\": failure_class,\n            \"message\": message,\n        }),\n    }\n}\n","numLines":201,"startLine":1,"totalLines":201}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_014CCnYnxNteMYP8ouaTBLdr","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a complete picture of the codebase. Let me map out what's been done and what's next.\n\n**Completed (Loops 1-6):**\n1. Domain model, workspace init, flow discovery\n2. Stage contracts, payload types, renderers\n3. Workspace governance, effective config, active project\n4. Project/run record foundation (models, journal, services, queries)\n5. Agent execution facade (ports, service, stub adapter, session management)\n6. Standard preset run start - full straight-through execution\n\n**What Loop 6 explicitly excluded (from the code):**\n- No retry on failure (any failure halts the run)\n\n\n- No resume capability (run resume returns NotYetImplemented)\n- Non-passing QA/review outcomes are fatal (QaReviewOutcomeFailure)\n- No prompt review special handling (treated like any stage)\n- No cycle advancement\n- No attempt tracking beyond initial attempt=1\n\nLoop 7 is about implementing retry/remediation, prompt review, resume, and failure class semantics. I need to design the spec starting with retry policies - TransportFailure should be retryable with max 3 attempts and exponential backoff, while other failure classes have different handling rules.\n\nFor QA/review outcomes specifically, I'm thinking through how to handle non-passing results: RequestChanges should loop back to the implementation stage with an incremented cycle number and feed back the review feedback as context, while ConditionallyApproved should proceed but queue amendments for later.\n\nI'm realizing this touches on completion round semantics too—the spec distinguishes between work cycles (iterative delivery units) and completion rounds (deciding whether to continue or complete), so I need to be careful about when each increments. But that's getting into roadmap item 8 territory with the full amendment queue and acceptance behavior.\n\nFor now, I should narrow the focus on roadmap item 7 to two concrete things: mapping retry policies to specific failure classes with configurable max attempts, and implementing a resume mechanism that reads from snapshots and journals to skip completed stages and pick back up from where things failed. I need to map failure classes to retry behavior with a struct that tracks max attempts and whether a failure is terminal, then set defaults for each class—transport failures get three attempts, schema and domain validation get two, timeouts get two, cancellations are terminal, and QA review failures trigger remediation instead of immediate retry. When a QA or review stage requests changes, the run continues into a remediation cycle rather than failing outright.\n\nNow for the resume logic: when restarting a failed or paused run, I read the snapshot and journal to determine which stages completed, skip those, and resume from the stage that failed while maintaining the same stage plan and setting status back to running.\n\nFor PromptReview specifically, it's a planning-stage that can pause execution if the readiness check fails—letting users modify the prompt before resuming—but only this stage triggers a paused state rather than continuing normally.\n\nOne constraint I need to handle: starting a new run on a project with an active run should resume or explicitly fail rather than creating duplicate active runs.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the cancellation and timeout behavior—if either signal fires during a retry loop, the run must stop immediately without completing the current attempt.\n\nLooking at the remediation flow across stages, QA and Review stages that return RequestChanges should loop back to Implementation with an incremented cycle count, and I need to map out where AcceptanceQa fits into this pattern.\n\nThe engine refactoring needs to handle resume logic by loading completed stages from the journal and finding the right resume point, then support retry tracking per stage and remediation loops that route back to earlier stages.\n\nRefactoring the engine structure...\n\nI should verify that `StageCursor.retry()` and `advance_cycle()` already exist from earlier work—they handle attempt tracking and cycle increments, which is exactly what I need for this feature.\n\nNow I'm ready to write out the spec and identify which files need changes. I need to add tests for the retry and resume functionality, plus a test file for the retry policy itself, and make sure the stub backend can simulate configurable retry-then-succeed scenarios. Looking at the existing journal events, `StageEntered` already captures cycle and attempt information, so retries would just be another `StageEntered` with an incremented attempt number, and `CycleAdvanced` handles remediation cycles. But I'm realizing we need a distinct event to capture when a stage fails without terminating the entire run—something to distinguish between a retriable failure and a terminal one. The contract evaluation currently treats non-passing outcomes as errors, but for remediation flows I need a way to distinguish between actual failures and outcomes like RequestChanges that should trigger a different path. Option A seems cleanest—keep the contract API unchanged and let the engine inspect the specific failure class to decide whether to retry, remediate, or fail entirely.\n\nBut wait, if evaluate returns an error, I lose the bundle entirely, and I need to persist those review findings as durable history even when the outcome doesn't pass. So I need to restructure this: split the outcome checking from evaluation itself. The engine would call evaluate without the outcome check to get the bundle, persist it, then separately check the outcome and decide what to do next. This way the valuable review data gets saved regardless of whether it passes.\n\nExamining the current code structure...\n\nRefactoring the method...\n\nI think the cleanest approach is adding `evaluate_and_classify` that returns both the validated bundle and an optional review outcome, so the engine can persist the bundle first and then decide how to handle the outcome separately. This keeps the validation logic clean and gives the engine full control over remediation decisions.\n\nNow for the `Paused` status—it's currently defined but never actually used. When prompt review indicates the run isn't ready, the engine should transition to paused and wait for external signals before continuing. persist the payload/artifact (the review happened)\n2. Set status to Paused\n3. Set the cursor to the next stage (Planning, since prompt review is done)\n4. Return to CLI with a message \"Prompt needs revision, run paused\"\n\nThen `run resume` can pick up from the planning stage.\n\nActually wait - if prompt review says \"not ready\", should we pause and wait for the user to revise the prompt? Or should we just fail? The spec says prompt review is \"optional by config\" but doesn't specify the non-ready behavior clearly.\n\nLooking at the readiness field in PlanningPayload, if `ready` is false, the prompt isn't ready to proceed. The natural behavior is to pause so the user can revise and resume. This is a clean use of the Paused state.\n\nThe roadmap puts prompt review in Loop 7, so I should include it. The key flow is: PromptReview runs if enabled, continues normally if ready, pauses with a message if not ready, then resume skips PromptReview and continues from Planning. Since PromptReview is a Planning-family stage, a false readiness would pass domain validation and contract evaluation would succeed.\n\nNow I'm thinking through what happens when the engine resumes - it needs to inspect the payload to check readiness, which is stage-specific logic that only PromptReview uses.\n\nFor the resume mechanism itself, I need to clarify the state transitions: read the snapshot to find where execution stopped, check the journal for completed stages, generate a new run ID, create a fresh ActiveRun with the cursor positioned at the first incomplete stage, set status back to Running, and continue execution from there.\n\nBut there's a tension with the monotonic cycle counters - if I create a new run ID, should those counters reset or carry over from the failed attempt? The spec says cycle numbers must be monotonic, which suggests they should persist across the resume boundary, but I need to think through whether a \"run\" represents a single execution attempt or something broader. -reset status to Running, restore the active_run with the cursor positioned at the resume point, and add a RunResumed journal event to track the continuation. For a failed run, I'd need to read back through the journal to find the last completed stage, calculate where to pick up from, then continue execution from there. I'm also thinking through how the attempt counter should behave during resume.\n\nWhen resuming, the attempt counter should reset to 1 for the resumed stage since we're starting a fresh execution context, even though the cycle numbers stay monotonic. The RunResumed event marks this boundary, and the run_id carries through since it's the same logical run.\n\nFor paused runs, it's simpler—we just continue from the next stage since the cursor was already positioned there. I also need to enhance the test backend adapter to support failure-then-succeed scenarios, and add a StageFailed journal event to track retryable failures.\n\nNow I'm working through the journal event types we need: StageFailed for when a stage fails but might be retried, and RunResumed for when execution picks back up. The tricky part is handling remediation cycles—when QA or Review requests changes, we need to persist that feedback and artifact, but we can't mark the stage as completed or we'd skip it on resume. I need to think through how to track that a stage ran but produced a non-passing outcome that requires re-execution.\n\nSo the flow would be: Planning and Implementation complete normally in cycle 1, then QA runs and returns RequestChanges. We record that QA completed with that outcome, emit a CycleAdvanced event to move to cycle 2, and then Implementation runs again followed by QA. The journal captures the full sequence with each stage entry and completion, including the outcome that triggered the cycle advancement.\n\nThis means I need to add an optional outcome field to the stage_completed event to track what result the stage produced. I also need to adjust the contract evaluation logic so it returns the full bundle even when outcomes don't pass, rather than just failing the evaluation. Then I can map which stages trigger which remediation paths—like prompt_review feeding back into planning.\n\nLooking at the main workflow stages, I'm thinking through how QA and Review stage failures should loop back. When QA requests changes, it should advance to the next cycle and re-enter at implementation. Same with Review—RequestChanges bumps the cycle and loops back to implementation. The completion panel, acceptance QA, and final review stages will handle their own remediation logic separately. I'm also wondering how ConditionallyApproved outcomes should be handled in this flow. I'm mapping out the full scope for Loop 7 — retry policies, stage-level retry mechanics with attempt tracking and backoff, resuming from paused runs, prompt review pause behavior, and how different QA outcomes flow through (RequestChanges cycles back, Rejected terminates, ConditionallyApproved proceeds with amendments queued for later). I'll need new journal events to track these state transitions, though I can probably consolidate them rather than creating separate event types. The amendment queue processing itself and completion panel semantics stay in Loop 8.\n\nNow I'm ready to write out the actual spec with clear, actionable details. StageEntered(attempt 1) → [fails, retryable] → StageEntered(attempt 2) → StageCompleted\n\nThe journal already captures the attempt number in StageEntered. If attempt 2 follows attempt 1 without a StageCompleted in between, it's implicit that attempt 1 failed. But for clarity and debuggability, it's better to have an explicit `StageFailed` event.\n\nSo I'm adding `StageFailed` to record when a stage attempt fails with a failure class but the run continues through retry or remediation, and `RunResumed` to track when a failed or paused run gets resumed. Both become new variants in JournalEventType.\n\nNow I'm mapping out the implementation: I need a new retry_policy module to define RetryPolicy and default policies per failure class, then update the engine to handle the retry loop, remediation, resume, and prompt review flows. I'll also need to extend the run record model with the new event types and ResumeInfo, add event builders to the journal, implement resume handling in the CLI, and update contracts with an evaluate_permissive method.\n\nAdding error variants for ResumeFailed and RemediationExhausted to the shared error module, configuring the stub backend to support fail-then-succeed behavior for testing, and writing comprehensive tests for all the new retry and resume logic.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4524,"cache_read_input_tokens":53892,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4524},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"04681ab0-f55e-4c96-b8ca-61b2a1e590bf","uuid":"d1eda606-2888-4c8f-a6fe-cf4f7a47d90d"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_014CCnYnxNteMYP8ouaTBLdr","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have a thorough understanding of the codebase. Let me write the spec for the next feature.\n\n# Feature: Retry, Remediation, Resume, and Failure Class Semantics\n\n## Description\nImplement the retry/remediation layer, run resume capability, prompt review pause behavior, and failure-class-driven retry policies for the workflow engine. Currently (Loop 6), any stage failure immediately terminates the run. This feature adds: (1) configurable retry policies mapped to each `FailureClass`, with per-stage attempt tracking; (2) remediation cycles when QA or Review stages return `RequestChanges`, looping back to the implementation stage with an incremented cycle number; (3) `run resume` to continue a failed or paused run from the last durable stage boundary; (4) prompt review pause semantics where `readiness.ready == false` pauses the run for user revision. These behaviors are required by delivery roadmap item 7 and core invariants: \"Cancellation and timeout must immediately halt retries,\" \"Resume is allowed only from durable stage boundaries,\" and \"Cycle and completion round numbers are monotonic and independent.\"\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] A `RetryPolicy` struct maps each `FailureClass` to max attempts and terminal/retryable classification. Default policies: `TransportFailure` → max 3 attempts; `SchemaValidationFailure` → max 2; `DomainValidationFailure` → max 2; `Timeout` → max 2; `Cancellation` → terminal (0 retries); `QaReviewOutcomeFailure` → not retried (triggers remediation or terminal depending on outcome).\n- [ ] The engine retry loop increments `StageCursor.attempt` on each retry and emits `StageFailed` + `StageEntered` journal events per attempt. Cancellation signal during a retry loop immediately halts all further retries for that stage.\n- [ ] When a QA or Review stage (but NOT `CompletionPanel`, `AcceptanceQa`, or `FinalReview`) returns `RequestChanges`, the engine persists the validation payload/artifact, emits a `CycleAdvanced` journal event, increments the cycle number, and loops execution back to the `Implementation` stage. Follow-up amendments from the review payload are passed as invocation context to the re-executed implementation stage.\n- [ ] When a QA or Review stage returns `Rejected`, the run fails terminally with `QaReviewOutcomeFailure`. When `ConditionallyApproved`, execution continues to the next stage and the `follow_up_or_amendments` are appended to the `amendment_queue` in the run snapshot.\n- [ ] Maximum remediation cycles per run is configurable (default 3). Exceeding the limit fails the run with a `RemediationExhausted` error.\n- [ ] `StageContract::evaluate_permissive` performs schema validation + semantic validation + rendering WITHOUT the outcome check, returning `ValidatedBundle` even for non-passing validation payloads. The engine calls this, persists the bundle, then separately inspects the `ReviewOutcome` to decide remediation vs continue vs fail.\n- [ ] `run resume` reads the snapshot (must be `Failed` or `Paused`) and journal, identifies completed stages via `StageCompleted` journal events, sets status back to `Running`, restores `active_run` with the cursor at the first incomplete stage (attempt reset to 1), appends a `RunResumed` journal event, and continues execution. The run_id is preserved across resume.\n- [ ] `run resume` on a `NotStarted`, `Running`, or `Completed` snapshot returns a clear error.\n- [ ] When the `PromptReview` stage produces a payload with `readiness.ready == false`, the engine persists the payload/artifact, sets `RunStatus::Paused`, clears `active_run`, and returns with a descriptive message. The user may revise the prompt and run `ralph-burning run resume` to continue from the `Planning` stage.\n- [ ] `run start` on a project with status `Failed` or `Paused` returns a clear error directing the user to `run resume`.\n- [ ] New `JournalEventType` variants: `StageFailed` (stage_id, cycle, attempt, failure_class, message, will_retry: bool) and `RunResumed` (run_id, resume_stage, cycle). Existing `CycleAdvanced` event builder is implemented (builder already referenced in enum but never constructed).\n- [ ] `StubBackendAdapter` gains `with_transient_failure(stage_id, fail_count)` that fails the first N invocations for a stage and then succeeds, enabling retry and remediation test scenarios.\n- [ ] Unit tests cover: retry exhaustion → run failure; retry success on second attempt; remediation cycle triggered by QA `RequestChanges`; remediation limit exceeded; resume from failed run skips completed stages; resume from paused prompt-review run; cancellation halts retry loop; `ConditionallyApproved` queues amendments and proceeds.\n- [ ] State invariant: after any failure mode (retry exhaustion, remediation exhaustion, cancellation during retry, resume validation failure), the run snapshot is in a consistent terminal or resumable state — `Failed` with `active_run == None`, or `Paused` with `active_run == None`. No partial `Running` state is left behind.\n\n## Files to Modify/Create\n- `src/contexts/workflow_composition/retry_policy.rs` (new) — `RetryPolicy` struct with `FailureClass` → max-attempts mapping, `default_policy()`, `is_retryable()`, `max_remediation_cycles()`.\n- `src/contexts/workflow_composition/mod.rs` — Export new `retry_policy` module.\n- `src/contexts/workflow_composition/engine.rs` — Major refactor: add `execute_standard_run_with_retry()` (or extend existing), implement per-stage retry loop with attempt tracking, remediation cycle logic (QA/Review → Implementation loop-back with cycle increment), prompt review pause handling, and `resume_standard_run()` entry point that loads journal, skips completed stages, and continues.\n- `src/contexts/workflow_composition/contracts.rs` — Add `evaluate_permissive()` method that skips `check_outcome()`, returning `ValidatedBundle` for non-passing outcomes.\n- `src/contexts/project_run_record/model.rs` — Add `StageFailed` and `RunResumed` to `JournalEventType` enum.\n- `src/contexts/project_run_record/journal.rs` — Add `stage_failed_event()`, `run_resumed_event()`, and `cycle_advanced_event()` builder functions.\n- `src/cli/run.rs` — Implement `handle_resume()` wiring: validate workspace/project, check snapshot status is Failed or Paused, call `engine::resume_standard_run()`. Update `handle_start()` to reject `Failed`/`Paused` status with message directing to `run resume`.\n- `src/shared/error.rs` — Add `ResumeFailed { reason: String }`, `RemediationExhausted { cycle: u32, max: u32 }` variants to `AppError`.\n- `src/adapters/stub_backend.rs` — Add `with_transient_failure(stage_id, fail_count)` using internal `AtomicU32` counter to track per-stage invocation attempts and fail the first N.\n- `tests/unit/retry_policy_test.rs` (new) — Tests for retry policy defaults, retryable classification, terminal classification.\n- `tests/unit/workflow_engine_test.rs` — Add test cases for retry loops, remediation cycles, resume behavior, prompt review pause, cancellation during retry, amendment queueing on ConditionallyApproved.\n\n## Dependencies\n- Requires: Loop 6 (Standard Preset Run Start Orchestration) — provides the straight-through engine, stage commit logic, fail_run helper, and stub backend\n- Blocks: Loop 8 (Completion/Acceptance/Final-Review Behavior + Amendment Queue) — completion panel semantics, amendment processing, and acceptance/final-review remediation depend on the retry/remediation/resume infrastructure built here\n\n---"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4524,"cache_read_input_tokens":53892,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4524},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"04681ab0-f55e-4c96-b8ca-61b2a1e590bf","uuid":"34881f26-fc5a-4b4b-8817-836ec6edaa95"}
